\begin_layout Standard
The magnitude of the electric field at the photosensor is given by the sum
 of the electric fields of each of the waves,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E=E_{1}+E_{2}+E_{3}+E_{4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intensity is proportional to the square modulus of (1)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left|E\right|^{2} & = & (E_{1}+E_{2}+E_{3}+E_{4})(E_{1}^{*}+E_{2}^{*}+E_{3}^{*}+E_{4}^{*})\\
 & = & \left|E_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|E_{2}\right|^{2}+\left|E_{3}\right|^{2}+\left|E_{4}\right|^{2}+2Re(E_{1}E_{2}^{*})+2Re(E_{1}E_{3}^{*})\\
 &  & +2Re(E_{1}E_{4}^{*})+2Re(E_{2}E_{3}^{*})+2Re(E_{2}E_{4}^{*})+2Re(E_{3}E_{4}^{*})
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this particular case, we can write the (time-averaged) electric fields
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
E_{1} & = & E_{01}e^{ik_{1}x}\\
E_{2} & = & E_{01}e^{ik_{1}(x+2\Delta x)}\\
E_{3} & = & E_{02}e^{ik_{2}x}\\
E_{4} & = & E_{02}e^{ik_{2}(x+2\Delta x)}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting into (3), and after performing some trigonometric algebra,
 we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left|E\right|^{2} & = & 2\left[E_{01}^{2}+E_{02}^{2}+E_{01}^{2}\cos(2k_{1}\Delta x)+E_{02}^{2}\cos(2k_{2}\Delta x)\right.\nonumber \\
 &  & \left.+4E_{01}E_{02}\cos\left(k_{1}\Delta x\right)\cos\left(k_{2}\Delta x\right)\cos\left((k_{1}-k_{2})(\Delta x+2x)\right)\right]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\frac{E_{01}}{E_{02}}$
\end_inset

, and rewrite this as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
I\propto\frac{1}{2}\left|\frac{E}{E_{02}}\right|^{2} & = & 1+a^{2}+a\cos(2k_{1}\Delta x)+\cos(2k_{2}\Delta x)\nonumber \\
 &  & +4a\cos\left(k_{1}\Delta x\right)\cos\left(k_{2}\Delta x\right)\cos\left((k_{1}-k_{2})(\Delta x+2x)\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $2x$
\end_inset

 factor in the last term is just an offset that does not affect the shape
 of the curve, so we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Rewriting in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{0}$
\end_inset

, the frequency of the central mode, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\nu$
\end_inset

, the frequency separation between the modes, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
I & \propto & 1+a^{2}+a\cos\left(\frac{4\pi\nu_{0}\Delta x}{c}\right)+\cos\left(\frac{4\pi(\nu_{0}+\Delta\nu)\Delta x}{c}\right)\nonumber \\
 &  & +4a\cos\left(\frac{2\pi\nu_{0}\Delta x}{c}\right)\cos\left(\frac{2\pi(\nu_{0}+\Delta\nu)\Delta x}{c}\right)\cos\left(\frac{2\pi\Delta\nu\Delta x}{c}\right)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
